TI  - The effects of conservation-adaptation strategies under climate change on the integrated water resource management in the south karkheh watershed in Iran
T2  - SUSTAINABLE FUTURES
LA  - English
KW  - Crop pattern
KW  - Adaptation strategies
KW  - Climate change
KW  - WEAP
KW  - Agent-based model
KW  - MODELING FRAMEWORK
AB  - Climate change has caused severe water scarcity and drought, resulting in competition for water among users. Due to the multi-dimensional, multi-scale nature of water resources management, there is a need to integrate tools for the analysis of conservation-adaptation policies used for climate change mitigation. Therefore, the present study aims to provide a hydro-economic-behavioral model for the assessment of the potential effects of climate change and conservation-adaptation strategies on the management of conflicting interests relating to water in three sub-catchments of the South Karkheh basin in Iran. This model was used to compare the effects of the conservation-adaptation strategies under climate change using a Multi-Objective Optimization Model, a Water Evaluation and Planning (WEAP) model, and finally an agent-based model. The agent-based model was used to analyze the cooperative and non-cooperative behaviors of farmers toward the strategies. Analysis of the effects of the conservation-adaptation scenarios, such as irrigation efficiency improvement, water release from upstream dams, the ban on summer crop cultivation, deficit irrigation, and restricted summer cropping, revealed that the use of these scenarios can mitigate climate change in this region. The farmers' cooperative behaviors spurred by incentive policies (compensation payment, crop insurance prices, agricultural input subsidies, etc.) are not presumed to be the same in all regions. Due to more water availability in the upstream area of the South Karkheh basin, the farmers of this region are expected to be less willing to cooperate with implementing the conservation-adaptation scenarios, while the downstream farmers are likely to accept the scenarios, including irrigation efficiency improvement, more easily.
